Remarks: In external morphology, N. neonilae sp. nov. is very similar to N. bimaculata. However, it is distinguishable from the latter by the presence of a narrow longitudinal midline (mid-dorsal cephalic ridge) between cephalic patches (
Figures 5M, N, P
). In the original description of N. bimaculata, Coe (1901) wrote that the head had two oval, black or very dark brown patches in material from Victoria (British Columbia, Canada), Sitka (Alaska, USA), and Puget Sound (Washington, USA). Later, Coe (1905: pl. 2, figure 21) illustrated a specimen with two narrow triangular cephalic patches. Photographs of the similar specimens are provided in BOLD (http://v3.boldsystems.org/index.php/Taxbrowser_Taxonpage?taxid=939114). Dr. Frank Crandall (personal communication) regarded that specimens of N. bimaculata with oval and triangular cephalic patches belong to two different species. If this is the case, specimens with oval head spots should be assigned to N. bimaculata. Nipponnemertes neonilae sp. nov. is distinguished from N. bimaculata in the Northeast Pacific in having triangular patches by wider and darker cephalic patches.

